Please respond to CDR Roberta Lavin:  <mailto:Roberta.lavin@hhs.gov>
Roberta.lavin@hhs.gov Phone 202-358-2413  <?xml:namespace prefix = o ns =
"urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office" />

The Secretary's Command Center (SCC) is looking for two highly motivated 0-3
to 0-5 officers to supplement the current staff to provide 24/7 coverage.
The primary responsibility of each officer will be to ensure that
information and messages related to terrorism and other public health
emergencies are collected and disseminated from one central location in a
timely and coordinated manner.  In an effort to assure a well-rounded team
persons with technical expertise in computer systems and GIS, in addition to
clinical and response knowledge are being sought for these positions.
Additionally, during non-response periods officers will be responsible for
assisting the Office of the Assistant Secretary with other projects.

These positions are highly visible and require that the officers wear the
uniform daily and present a professional appearance.  Officers wishing to be
considered for this position must meet all CCRF membership requirements for
a fully qualified member or be able to be fully qualified within 6 months.
CCRF membership demonstrates a desire to be involved in and a commitment to
response activities.  Officers with clinical backgrounds are preferred,
however all officers with the required skill will be considered.

Please submit a CV and cover letter no later than 1/13/03 to CDR Roberta
Lavin:

 <mailto:Roberta.lavin@hhs.gov> Roberta.lavin@hhs.gov

202-358-2413

 A Top Secret clearance will be required.

Applicants need to be able to integrate systems and be proficient in the
latest software packages and applications.

 Department of Health and Human Services

Office of the Assistant Secretary of Public Health Emergency Preparedness

Secretary's Command Center



Position Title, Series and Grade:  Public Health Preparedness Logistics
Officer, 0-5



Number of Positions:  4



Organization Location and Duty Station:  Health and Human Services, Office
of the Secretary, Office of the Assistant Secretary of Public Health
Emergency Preparedness, Secretary's Command Center, Washington, DC



Area of Consideration:  PHS Commissioned Corps officers grades 0-2 to 0-4



Skill Set Needed:




Special Skills - Desired


*       Communications Officer

*       Understanding of procurement and maintenance of communication
hardware and software
*       Ability to interface with other HHS agencies to assure proper
programming and functioning of equipment

*       Logistics Officer

*       Ability to maintain surplus materials and supplies in an organized,
readily accessible, clean and useable manner
*       Ability to identify deficiencies in surplus materials and supplies
*       Ability to maintain a database to track all current inventories of
equipment
*       Knowledge of logistical requirements and operational activities for
health and medical response during major disasters or emergencies

*       Information Technology

*       Knowledge of high availability computer system architectures,
operating systems, storage, and computer networking, including
infrastructure design and hardware and software configuration


Skills - Required


*       Response

*       Fully qualified member of CCRF or DMAT
*       Knowledge and understanding of HHS/OASPHEP/OEP/NDMS
*       Prior participation in a response activity

*       Other

*       Ability to communicate effectively both orally and in writing
*       Computer literate in Microsoft word, excel, access, and PowerPoint



Duty Hours:  The Secretary's Command Center (SCC) will be operational 24/7
and will be staffed by a minimum of one officer at all times.  The shifts
will be assigned based on the needs of the SCC.

 Deputy Director, Secretary's Command Center


PHS 0-5/6 billet


During response operations, the incumbent of this position will be assigned
to assist the SCC Director in the management of the SCC that facilitates the
activation of the NDMS to deploy to the field to render health and medical
assistance as needed during special events, disasters, major transportation
accidents and other activities requiring team deployment. The incumbent
assists the SCC Director in the communication and information gathering and
distribution and serve as the point of contact with the field until the SERT
is operational in the field and able to take provide reports from the field.
The SCC will assume a support roll to ensure that all requests for
national-level guidance are met, required personnel and equipment are
available, and that HHS leadership is appropriately briefed on response
activities.


MAJOR DUTIES AND RESPONSIBILITIES


During periods of readiness, the incumbent is responsible to the SCC
Director.  He/she shall assist the SCC Director to ensure that the SCC is in
a continual state of readiness for activation. This includes maintaining a
cadre of highly skilled SCC personnel.  The incumbent shall support and
participate in the process to identify, develop, coordinate, and implement
training that addresses SCC related issues, including but not limited to
issues raised in After Action Reports. He/she shall assist in the analyzing
and implementation of technology that enhances the SCC function.  The
incumbent will be required to work an irregular work shift to provide
readiness coverage of the SCC.  In the absence of the SCC Director the
incumbent shall execute the duties of the SCC Director required to maintain
the SCC in a continual state of readiness for activation. Listed below are
the duties and responsibilities associated with maintaining the EOC in the
proper state of readiness.  The incumbent shall support and assist the SCC
Director to ensure that the listed readiness responsibilities are executed
in a prompt and proficient manner:

1.                  Responsible for recruiting and maintaining a cadre of
highly skilled SCC personnel that are available, as needed, to work in the
SCC when activated.  Interviews candidates and selects staff for positions
in the SCC.

2.                  Represents the SCC in dealings with internal as well as
other Federal, State and local entities.  Promote and maintain effective
working relationships with the various organizations.

3.                  Develops, documents, and delivers monthly training for
all SCC personnel. Training includes:

 Overview and Update - Provides the big picture of where the SCC fits into
the HHS response to stand-by events, emergencies and disasters.  Also
provides participants with an overview of recent changes.

Processes and Technology - Provides in-depth explanations of the processes
and tools used to perform SCC tasks. Training will be hands-on whenever
possible.

Exercise - Designed to practice the processes and technologies taught.
Exercise will be coached as needed.

Review - An opportunity for participants to rate the effectiveness of the
training and suggest topics/methodologies for future training.

4.                  Compiles After Action Reports following all activations
of the SCC to identify all issues and/or suggestions that would increase SCC
effectiveness.  Develops, documents, implements, and trains to correct
issues identified in After Action Reports.

 5.                  Convenes working groups of necessary personnel and
other agency personnel, as required, to address issues of policy and
procedure that would increase the SCC's effectiveness in support of disaster
response efforts.

 6.                  Analyzes trends in technology and products that may be
adapted for use in the SCC.  Must be able to analyze a product to ensure it
interacts seamlessly with existing technology, significantly contributes to
SCC operations, and is capable of being successfully operated by
intermittent users.

7.                  Designs, implements, documents, trains, and maintains
database applications such as an incident log, personnel tracking, etc. to
support SCC operations.

8.                  Ensures the operational readiness of all equipment used
to support SCC operations.

9.                  Independently proposes or acts on management
considerations relative to the development of procedures for the SCC
personnel; revises or changes the emphasis of existing procedures, or
terminates existing procedures as a result of policy changes.  Deals
effectively with other EOCs on matters within their areas of responsibility.


10.              Independently provides technical advice to external
organizations and/or groups representing the SCC's interest on program
matters involving EOC policy and procedures.

11.              Establishes and implements administrative policies, plans,
and operational procedures that support SCC operational capabilities.

12.              Reviews response manuals, plans, and other written
materials relating to national emergency preparedness and response to
disasters of our partner agencies.  Integrates concepts into current SCC
operations to eliminate duplication of effort and compatibility with other
partner agencies to ensure that optimal information flow is established and
maintained.

During response operations, the incumbent is responsible to the SCC
Director.  He/she

shall assist the SCC Director in the management of all activities necessary
to provide support to a wide range of Federal health and medical resources
being used during a disaster. He/she shall support the management of the
day-to-day operations of the SCC.  The incumbent shall be required to work
altered and extends shifts during response operations and SCC activations,
(including nights, weekends and holidays).  The incumbent shall work closely
with and support the SCC Director in the multifaceted aspects of SCC
activation.  The incumbent shall work in the SCC and maintain a continuum of
management and operations in the absence of the SCC Director.  Listed below
are the duties and responsibilities associated with an EOC activation.  The
incumbent shall support and assist the SCC Director to ensure proper and
proficient execution of the following duties and responsibilities:

1.                  Ensures that the SCC organization and operations are
appropriate to effectively support response operations.  Coordinates the
activation and deployment of all resources to the incident scene.

2.                  Provides general guidance and supervision of the work of
SCC staff to assure that they are trained and provided with the equipment,
supplies, support, etc., necessary to satisfactorily carry out their
assignments and activities.  Establishes appropriate staffing levels in the
SCC to effectively support response operations.  Staff may range from 3-30+
during activations and may extend for several months.  Exercises a high
degree of judgement and professional leadership in coordinating all
activities of the SCC and guiding the staff in solving difficult problems.

3.                  Plans and assigns work; sets goals and establishes
priorities; evaluates performance of subordinates; identifies training needs
during activations; hears staff complaints and takes appropriate action as
necessary.

4.                  Keeps the various agencies of jurisdiction informed on
all matters affecting the effective utilization of health and medical
assets;

5.                  Ensures that multi-agency or inter-agency coordination
is accomplished effectively within the SCC; develops current and accurate
assessments of the disaster situation, PHS response activities, and the
preparation of informational summaries; reviews all written reports and
communications prior to submission to the Assistant Secretary and the
Secretary; keeps HHS administration informed on all matters regarding the
response activities; and keeps HHS liaison officers assigned to other agency
operations centers current on response operations.

 6.                  Participates in a daily briefing with all deployed
teams to maintain current information from the resources assigned.

 7.                  Performs other related duties as required, including
tasks normally performed by other SCC personnel to assist in the efficacy of
SCC operations.



 FACTORS



Factor 1 - Knowledge Required by the Position

Knowledge

Comprehensive knowledge of the HHS Response System, their organizational
structures, operating procedures, safety practices, terminology, and
administration.

Extensive knowledge of the Federal Response Plan, particularly the ESFs that
may apply to HHS during a full activation of the Federal Response Plan (FRP)
and other HHS Memorandums of Understanding requiring HHS actions.

 Knowledge of other disaster response organizations and their missions (i.e.
Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA), Red Cross, National
Transportation Safety Board (NTSB), Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)
and other Non-governmental Organizations (NGOs).

 Requires detailed knowledge of office activities, procedures, techniques
and practices in order to control and monitor work assignments, shifting
priorities as necessary to accomplish a smooth, efficient work flow.

Comprehensive knowledge of National Interagency Incident Management
System/Incident Command System (NIIMS/ICS).




Skills




Must be proficient in the advanced features of Word, Powerpoint, Access and
Excel.  In-depth knowledge of database programs to include skills in
performing advanced queries, inputting and exporting data, implementing,
documenting, and maintaining database applications such as an incident log,
personnel tracking, etc.

Must be able to assimilate large amounts of information from various sources
into clear concise reports, briefings and situational assessments.  Must be
able to synthesize divergent information into an EOC Action Plan.

 Must have excellent Interpersonal skills; the ability to interact with
persons at all levels of government and civilian agencies.

Ability to resolve adverse issues in a diplomatic manner to cause a positive
reflection on HHS supervisory and management skills that motivate employees
to produce at the highest output level for efficient operations in a
stressful work environment.

 Competent in the development and use of integrated action planning concepts
and processes.


 Abilities


 Ability to assemble detailed information on operational situations,
evaluate the information to determine the rate of progress toward meeting
established goals, and present a document to management together with
recommendations for overcoming any problems identified.

 Ability to design, document and conduct complex training programs and
exercises that simulate tasks and scenarios likely to be encountered during
SCC activations.

Must be able to analyze a product to ensure it interacts seamlessly with
existing technology, significantly contributes to SCC operations, and is
capable of being successfully operated by intermittent users.

Ability to communicate effectively, orally, and in writing, with managers
and employees within the government and emergency medical personnel outside
the government who are part of the State and local community.

Ability to effectively manage personnel, specialized equipment, and support
resources during a response situation.  Ability to troubleshoot software
applications and other electronics as needed to support SCC operations.

 Ability to implement ICS principles within the established Departmental
guidelines.

Ability to conduct briefings and planning meetings.

Ability to manage response systems and activities, anticipate resource
problems, and plan the appropriate actions.

 Ability to motivate personnel and form effective work groups.

 Ability to work with little or no supervision.



Factor 2 - Supervisory Controls

 Work is performed under the very general direction of the supervisor.
Assignments are made in terms of broad objectives to be achieved.  Within
the accepted parameters of the assignment, the incumbent is responsible for
independent planning and organizing work, coordinating with personnel inside
and outside the Federal government, and advising the supervisor of
controversial findings, issues, or problems with potential widespread
impact.  Completed work is reviewed in terms of overall effectiveness in
achieving intended objectives.




Factor 3 - Guidelines




Guidelines consist of general administrative policies, operating procedures,
techniques, practices, etc., which require considerable adaptation and/or
interpretation for application to issues and problems encountered.
Administrative policies and precedent provide a basic outline of results
desired, but do not go into detail as to the methods used to accomplish the
work.  The incumbent must use judgement and ingenuity in the development of
emergency response plans, strategies, and procedures.



Factor 4 - Complexity



HHS is the lead Federal agency for emergency preparedness in the health and
medical services. Work includes a broad range of activities related to the
Department's overall emergency preparedness program and within the Office of
the Assistant Secretary of Public Health Emergency Preparedness, its
policies, plans, programs, and operational activities.  Frequently, the
incumbent independently decides what needs to be done based on each
assignment, the outcome required, and the issues involved.



The position requires attention to step-by-step progression of a large
number of separate activities, and logistical planning to cause a number of
unrelated actions to happen at the proper time in the proper sequence.  The
task is rendered much more difficult by the fact that so much depends upon
the coordination and cooperation of various branches within OASPHEP and
other agencies.  The tasks are further hampered by the unpredictable nature,
time and duration of activations.  In addition to causing actions to occur,
the position requires the ability to analyze what is happening, what if
anything is going wrong, and what to do about it.  A high degree of
analytical ability is needed to assess the situation and respond
accordingly.


Factor 5 - Scope and Effect




The SCC is the focal point of information released to the HHS community
during response operations; it collects, analyzes, synthesizes and reports
all response operation activities.  In media sensitive events, the SCC
Director may work closely with OASPHEP management, HHS Public Affairs
Officers, and others to prepare press releases about an event.  The
incumbent's performance has an effect on the prestige and professional
reputation of the OASPHEP.  A Top Secret will be required for the position.

Factor 6 - Personal Contacts



Incumbent relates directly with the entire OASPHEP staff, agency personnel
staff, Federal, State and local government representatives, NDMS partner
Federal agencies (DoD, VA, and FEMA) and personnel from the NDMS teams.


Factor 7 - Purpose of the Contacts


Contacts are to discuss and coordinate technical issues, render advice and
assistance, resolve problems involving interrelationships of manpower needs
in emergency preparedness and response activities.


Factor 8 - Physical Demands


Persons are expected to be able to be CCRF fully qualified.


Factor 9 - Work Environment


The work is performed in an office setting with some travel to meetings,
conferences, and exercises.  The incumbent is responsible for activating the
SCC.  The incumbent is required to work irregular work schedules (evenings,
nights, and weekends).Work may be subject to tight deadlines and stressful
conditions during emergency assignments.


